Description: CVE-2026-33536 - Fix incorrect return value causing pointer
 increment past end of stack buffer in InterpretImageFilename.
 .
 Due to an incorrect return value on certain platforms, a pointer is
 incremented past the end of a buffer on the stack, which could result
 in an out-of-bounds write. This patch validates the return value of
 FormatLocaleString against strlen of the result pattern, and uses the
 validated length for both the bounds check and pointer advancement.
 .
 This applies on top of the CVE-2025-55298 rewrite of InterpretImageFilename
 which introduced the cursor-based parsing with IsValidFormatSpecifier.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/commit/ee4468a8ab0635fcaa9c561e583c56ada3b1b721
Author: ImageMagick Developers <support@imagemagick.org>
Last-Update: 2026-03-31

--- a/MagickCore/image.c
+++ b/MagickCore/image.c
@@ -1,7 +1,8 @@
               format_specifier[MagickPathExtent];

             size_t
-              length = cursor-specifier_start;
+              length = cursor-specifier_start,
+              pattern_length;

             ssize_t
               count;
@@ -10,10 +11,13 @@
               "%%%.*s%c",(int) length,specifier_start,*cursor);
             count=FormatLocaleString(pattern,sizeof(pattern),format_specifier,
               value);
-            if ((count <= 0) || ((p-filename+count) >= MagickPathExtent))
+            pattern_length=strlen(pattern);
+            if ((count <= 0) || ((size_t) count != pattern_length))
+              return(0);
+            if ((p-filename+pattern_length) >= MagickPathExtent)
               return(0);
             (void) CopyMagickString(p,pattern,MagickPathExtent-(p-filename));
-            p+=strlen(pattern);
+            p+=pattern_length;
             cursor++;
             continue;
           }
Description: CVE-2026-33535 - Fix out-of-bounds write of a zero byte in X11 display
 ImageMagick prior to 7.1.2-18 has an out-of-bounds write of a zero byte in
 the X11 display interaction path (XImageWindowCommand function in
 MagickCore/display.c). The code appends a digit character to the delta
 buffer without checking if the buffer has space, which can write past the
 end of the buffer. This patch adds a bounds check against MagickPathExtent
 before writing to the buffer.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/commit/d3af057fb9d3666762ca3731c2360f544f607f88
Author: Cristy <urban-warrior@imagemagick.org>
Last-Update: 2026-03-31

--- a/MagickCore/display.c
+++ b/MagickCore/display.c
@@ -6704,14 +6704,21 @@ static DisplayCommand XImageWindowCommand(Display *display,

   if ((key_symbol >= XK_0) && (key_symbol <= XK_9))
     {
+      size_t
+        length;
+
       if (((last_symbol < XK_0) || (last_symbol > XK_9)))
         {
           *delta='\0';
           resource_info->quantum=1;
         }
       last_symbol=key_symbol;
-      delta[strlen(delta)+1]='\0';
-      delta[strlen(delta)]=Digits[key_symbol-XK_0];
+      length=strlen(delta);
+      if (length < MagickPathExtent)
+        {
+          delta[length]=Digits[key_symbol-XK_0];
+          delta[length+1]='\0';
+        }
       resource_info->quantum=StringToLong(delta);
       return(NullCommand);
     }
Description: CVE-2026-32636 - Fix out-of-bounds write in ConvertUTF16ToUTF8
 ImageMagick contains a heap-buffer-overflow in the ConvertUTF16ToUTF8
 helper function in MagickCore/xml-tree.c. The buffer is resized to
 exactly *length bytes but a null terminator is written at utf8[*length],
 one byte past the end of the allocated buffer. This corrects the
 off-by-one by allocating (*length+1) bytes.
Origin: upstream, commit:361b42c91d173cfb4bd8f39898c599feef6a1e55
Author: Dirk Lemstra <dirk@lemstra.org>
Last-Update: 2026-03-24

--- a/MagickCore/xml-tree.c
+++ b/MagickCore/xml-tree.c
@@ -1276,7 +1276,7 @@ static char *ConvertUTF16ToUTF8(const ch
     }
   }
   *length=(size_t) j;
-  utf8=(char *) ResizeQuantumMemory(utf8,*length,sizeof(*utf8));
+  utf8=(char *) ResizeQuantumMemory(utf8,(*length+1),sizeof(*utf8));
   if (utf8 != (char *) NULL)
     utf8[*length]='\0';
   return(utf8);
